# Security Review: app.js

## Summary

The file is a 22-line Express app with two hardcoded GET endpoints (`/health`, `/users`). There is **no user input handling, no database, no auth, no file I/O, and no dynamic response content** — so most OWASP Top 10 categories (injection, SSRF, deserialization, broken access control logic, etc.) don't currently have an attack surface here. That said, there are several real hardening gaps worth fixing now so they don't regress once real logic is added.

I'll be straight: I'm not going to invent vulnerabilities that aren't present. Below are the actual issues.

---

## Findings

### 1. Missing security response headers (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration)
Express ships with no hardening headers by default. `X-Powered-By: Express` is sent, leaking the framework.

**Fix:** use `helmet`.
```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet());
```

### 2. No CORS policy defined (A05)
With no CORS configuration, behavior depends on where the API is consumed. Make the intent explicit rather than relying on defaults.
```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example'], methods: ['GET'] }));
```

### 3. No rate limiting / DoS protection (A04: Insecure Design)
`/users` and `/health` can be hammered freely. Add a limiter before any real endpoints ship.
```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100, standardHeaders: true, legacyHeaders: false }));
```

### 4. PII exposure on `/users` (A01: Broken Access Control, A02: Cryptographic Failures)
`/users` returns email addresses (PII) to any unauthenticated caller. Even with mock data, this is the template future code will copy. Establish an auth boundary now:
```js
function requireAuth(req, res, next) {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token || !isValidToken(token)) return res.sendStatus(401);
  next();
}
app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => { /* ... */ });
```
Also consider returning only fields the caller is authorized to see (drop `email` for non-admin roles).

### 5. No request logging / monitoring (A09: Security Logging and Monitoring Failures)
No way to detect abuse or incidents.
```js
const morgan = require('morgan');
app.use(morgan('combined'));
```

### 6. Listening on all interfaces implicitly
`app.listen(3000, ...)` binds to `0.0.0.0`. If this is only for a reverse proxy on the same host, bind explicitly:
```js
app.listen(3000, '127.0.0.1', () => { /* ... */ });
```

### 7. No graceful shutdown / error handling
Unhandled errors in future routes will crash the process. Add a final error handler and process guards:
```js
app.use((err, req, res, _next) => {
  console.error(err);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' }); // don't leak err.message
});
process.on('unhandledRejection', (e) => console.error(e));
```

### 8. `/health` leaks server time
`new Date().toISOString()` is minor, but health endpoints are often the first probe attackers use. Keep it minimal:
```js
app.get('/health', (_req, res) => res.json({ status: 'ok' }));
```

### 9. No body parser limits (pre-emptive, A04)
Once you add `express.json()`, cap the payload size to prevent memory-exhaustion:
```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '100kb' }));
```

### 10. HTTPS / TLS not addressed
Assumed to be terminated upstream. If not, enforce HSTS via helmet and redirect HTTP→HTTPS. If TLS is terminated at a proxy, also set `app.set('trust proxy', 1)` so `req.ip` and rate-limit keys are accurate.

---

## Things I explicitly did NOT flag (because they don't apply here)
- SQL/NoSQL/command/LDAP injection — no query construction or user input
- SSRF — no outbound requests
- Path traversal — no filesystem access
- Insecure deserialization — no user-controlled parsing
- XSS — responses are JSON, no HTML templating
- CSRF — no state-changing endpoints yet

## Recommended consolidated patch
```js
const express = require('express');
const helmet = require('helmet');
const cors = require('cors');
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const morgan = require('morgan');

const app = express();
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.set('trust proxy', 1);

app.use(helmet());
app.use(cors({ origin: ['https://your-frontend.example'], methods: ['GET'] }));
app.use(morgan('combined'));
app.use(express.json({ limit: '100kb' }));
app.use(rateLimit({ windowMs: 60_000, max: 100 }));

app.get('/health', (_req, res) => res.json({ status: 'ok' }));

app.get('/users', /* requireAuth, */ (_req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice' },
    { id: 2, name: 'Bob' },
  ]); // email removed until authz is in place
});

app.use((err, _req, res, _next) => {
  console.error(err);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});

const port = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(port, '0.0.0.0', () => console.log(`Server running on port ${port}`));

module.exports = app;
```

