Lines 11–16 expose user records including email addresses to any unauthenticated caller. Even with sample data, shipping this pattern becomes a leak the moment it's backed by a real store.

```js
app.get('/users', (req, res) => {
  res.json([
    { id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
    ...
  ]);
});
```

**Fix:** Require auth and filter fields per caller's permissions.

```js
const requireAuth = (req, res, next) => {
  const token = req.headers.authorization?.replace(/^Bearer\s+/i, '');
  if (!token) return res.status(401).json({ error: 'unauthorized' });
  try {
    req.user = jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET);
    next();
  } catch {
    return res.status(401).json({ error: 'invalid token' });
  }
};

app.get('/users', requireAuth, (req, res) => {
  // Only return emails if caller is admin
  const scrub = (u) => req.user.role === 'admin' ? u : { id: u.id, name: u.name };
  res.json(users.map(scrub));
});
```

---

### 2. Missing security headers (OWASP A05: Security Misconfiguration) — **Medium**

No `helmet` or equivalent. Responses lack `X-Content-Type-Options`, `Strict-Transport-Security`, `Content-Security-Policy`, `X-Frame-Options`, etc. Also, `X-Powered-By: Express` leaks the framework.

**Fix:**

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.disable('x-powered-by');
app.use(helmet({
  contentSecurityPolicy: { directives: { defaultSrc: ["'self'"] } },
  hsts: { maxAge: 31536000, includeSubDomains: true, preload: true },
}));
```

---

### 3. No rate limiting (OWASP A04) — **Medium**

Any client can hammer `/health` or `/users`. Combined with no auth on `/users`, this enables trivial enumeration/DoS.

**Fix:**

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60_000,
  max: 60,
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
}));
```

---

### 4. No CORS policy (OWASP A05) — **Medium**

Browsers will apply same-origin defaults, but without explicit config you'll either accidentally allow `*` later or break legitimate clients. Decide explicitly.

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://app.example.com'],
  methods: ['GET'],
  credentials: false,
}));
```

---

### 5. Binds to all interfaces on plain HTTP (OWASP A02: Cryptographic Failures) — **Medium**

`app.listen(3000)` binds to `0.0.0.0` and serves unencrypted HTTP. PII from `/users` would travel in the clear. Terminate TLS at a proxy (nginx / ALB / Cloudflare) or bind to loopback for local dev only.

```js
const host = process.env.HOST ?? '127.0.0.1';
const port = Number(process.env.PORT ?? 3000);
app.listen(port, host, () => console.log(`listening on ${host}:${port}`));
```

Put an HTTPS-terminating reverse proxy in front in production.

