Any client can hammer `/health` or `/users`. Combined with no auth on `/users`, this enables trivial enumeration/DoS.

**Fix:**

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
app.use(rateLimit({
  windowMs: 60_000,
  max: 60,
  standardHeaders: true,
  legacyHeaders: false,
}));
```

---

### 4. No CORS policy (OWASP A05) — **Medium**

Browsers will apply same-origin defaults, but without explicit config you'll either accidentally allow `*` later or break legitimate clients. Decide explicitly.

```js
const cors = require('cors');
app.use(cors({
  origin: ['https://app.example.com'],
  methods: ['GET'],
  credentials: false,
}));
```

---

### 5. Binds to all interfaces on plain HTTP (OWASP A02: Cryptographic Failures) — **Medium**

`app.listen(3000)` binds to `0.0.0.0` and serves unencrypted HTTP. PII from `/users` would travel in the clear. Terminate TLS at a proxy (nginx / ALB / Cloudflare) or bind to loopback for local dev only.

